before_annotation.answer:
Start with the retailer:
\[ \max_{p} (p - p_w) D(p)
 \]

implies that
\begin{equation}
D(p) + (p - p_w) D'(p) = 0.
\tag{1}
\end{equation}

which defines a function $p^*(p_w)$ (assuming that the objective function is concave). We have
\[ [2D'(p) + (p - p_w)D''(p)]dp^* - D'(p)dp_w = 0. \]
Hence, using equation 1, we obtain
\begin{equation} \frac{dp^*}{dp_w} = \frac{1}{2 - D(p)D''(p)/D'^2(p)}. \tag{2}
\end{equation}

Hence, $\frac{dp^*}{dp_w}$ is greater or less than $\frac{1}{2}$ if the demand function is convex or concave.
The manufacturer maximizes $(p_w - c)D(p^*(p_w))$.
\begin{equation}
D(p) + (p_w - c)D'(p)\frac{dp^*}{dp_w} = 0. 
\tag{3}
\end{equation} 

Equations 1–3 yield the desired result.

